climbs.name: Violent Threats From The Guidebook Bully

content.description: Start in a right-facing corner with a tricky move, then pull over a lip on jugs and run it out to the face above.  A series of horizontal, slopey rails will bring you to the anchor.
content.location: Immediately left of Ellie's Sweet Kiss

climbs.name: Tunnel of Love/Delightful Cacophony Funneled Within

content.description: An awkward move past the first bolt leads to a jug haul through the tunnel and to the chains. Pulling on the Block of Doom helps getting through.
content.protection: 5 bolts and a two-bolt anchor with two carabiners
content.location: Highest route on the left wall at the top of the large chimney in Eastern Block.

content.description: The cruxes are pulling two roofs throughout this climb. The anchors are in a poor location for belaying at the top or top roping. If you choose to lower and top rope your second you'll need to clean several draws on the way down.
content.location: The next route encountered on the Eastern Block climbing an obvious bolted arete at the start.

content.description: Steep slab route with good friction and positive, yet small edges.
content.location: You reach this route soon after entering the Eastern Block area. Look for a large block detached from the slabby face and start here. (Refer to photos posted here.)

content.description: This line drew my eye the first time I visited exit 38. Super techy slab moves on thin feet. Crux is getting to the small ledge directly below the 4th bolt. The style would make for a fantastic first .11 lead.
content.protection:
Climb to the right of 4 bolts and then connect with Space Face to the anchors.

We took the time to bolt thoughtfully, all of the hard moves are very well protected. 6 bolts total.Â Can be toproped by climbing impartial eclipse. Be sure to leave a directional on the 2nd to last bolt to avoid a swing.

climbs.name: The Ruins Of War
climbs.fa: Leland Windham, David Wolfe, Alec McMillan, May 2004

content.description: Pretty much regular EB route with good holds and a "walkable" part in the middle of the route.
content.location: Next to the right from the Ellie's Sweet Kiss

climbs.name: Piece Maker
climbs.fa: Leland Windham, David Wolfe, Alec McMillan, May 2004

content.description: Guidebook rates it at 5.7, but if climbing the line of bolts, I would not say it's any easier than 5.8s surrounding it.
content.location: To the right of EB-3, shortest route on this section of the wall with the lowest hanging chains

content.description: Climb around several small roofs at the begining up to steep and easier climbing above.
content.location: This is the second of two climbs encountered after entering trees on the trail past the large sun exposed wall.

content.description: A couple of thin moves gain awkward climbing passing the Block of Doom on the right, to a mantle and two bolts of slab to the chains.
content.protection: 6 bolts and a two-bolt anchor with two carabiners, shared with Tunnel of Love
content.location: Right-most route on wall on the rightside of the block of doom. The route meets the right side of the block.

content.description:
Mostly vertical climb up big jugs, with a great view of Snoqualmie Pass from the top. A new first bolt has been added recently in the wide slabby corner that marks the start. There's another bolto to the left for a 5.8 start and causes some rope drag so if you want to use that put a longer sling on it.

There's a bit of noise and a small bit where climber and belayer aren't visible. Yell loudly or use radios or rope signals.
content.protection:
8 bolts, two-bolt anchor with chains.

2-3 alpine draws since the rope zigzags quite a bit.
content.location: Right side of Eastern Block next to a big flake on the ground; farther to the right is all moss. A smaller flake under makes a decent anchor for light belayers. Rap down on a single 50m+ rope.

content.description: First route to the right of the gully below the Block of Doom. Shares anchor with Space Face and Sorry, We Came Early.
content.protection: 6 bolts and a two-bolt anchor with chains

content.description: Tech your way through the first few bolts, then find a no hands rest below the roof. Grab the big hold, clip the bolt if you can or just mantle. Finish at the chains on the big ledge.
content.location: The last route before the belay area goes up 20 feet go the Ellie's Sweet Kiss area. Pulls the obvious roof.

climbs.name: Ghosts Of War
climbs.fa: Leland Windham, David Wolfe, Alec McMillan, May 2004

content.description: Pretty standard for EB, fun lower part with much easier upper part. Chains below the dead tree.
content.location: Next to the EB-2 and to the left from the tree.

climbs.name: Ellie's Sweet Kiss
climbs.fa: Leland Windham, Garth Bruce & Bryan Burdo (2002)

content.description: No cruxes, all very easy. Heavily overrated. A fun jug haul climb though.
content.location:
The longest route on the larger more sun exposed face of the Eastern Block.

There are several other routes between 5.7 and 5.9 on this face as well.

content.description: One of the longest routes on this section of the wall. Upper part has a little overhang so it's a little different than the surrounding routes.
content.location: To the right of the tree and next to the EB-4. Note: exit 38 guidebook calls it EB-6, but it looks like it's just a typo, as EB-4 and EB-5 in the book refer to the same route (5.7)

content.description: Some slab climbing to start with leads up through a bunch of broken roofs with a distinctly alpine feel to some nice views at the top of the formation.
content.protection: 8 bolts to chains with perma-biners. Other than a small section near the start, could easily protect the entire climb with a standard rack.
content.location: One climb left of Kiss of the Crowbar. After the first three bolts, this route merges with the remainder of Kiss of the Crowbar.
